<DOC><DOCNO> ZF32-198-052 </DOCNO><DOCID>10 490 396</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computergram International  March 19 1991 n1635* Full Text COPYRIGHT Apt Data Services (England) 1991.andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>European commission issues directive on leased lines across theCommunity. (European Community)andM;</TITLE><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Leased LinesSingle European MarketEuropean Economic CommunityEuropean Community. Commission of the European CommunitiesData CommunicationsEurope.andM;</DESCRIPT><TEXT>EUROPEAN COMMISSION ISSUES DIRECTIVE ON LEASEDandM;LINES ACROSS THE COMMUNITYandM;The European Commission is attempting to guarantee open, harmonised access toleased lines across the Community, adopting a directive on the subject.andO;Discussion of the issue was initiated by vicepresident Filippo MariaPandolfi, who also proposed the breakup of the telecommunications statemonopolies' hold over the satellite market.andP;  The Commission describestelecommunications as &quot;the nervous system of a modern economy&quot; and notes thatleased lines are used not only for private corporate networks, but also forthe provision of valueadded services such as online access to databases,electronic messaging and electronic funds transfer.andP;  The directive tacklesinterconnection, supply and usage conditions and tariff principles.andP;  Itproposes that there should be no technical restrictions on interconnection ofleased lines and that regulatory restrictions be lifted.andP;  Companies wouldalso be required to disclose prices and notify users of price increases inadvance.andP;  The directive provides for a standard set of four types of leasedlines across the Community, splitting analogue and 64Kbps digital lines intotwo categories.andP;  The proposed directive still has to pass to the EuropeanCouncil for ratification, but assuming it is adopted, harmonised provisionfor both types of leased line will be in place by the time the directivecomes into force on January 1, 1992.andP;  The only exception are digital linesoperating at 2Mbps, which would have to be uniformly offered throughout theCommunity by July 1 1992.andO;</TEXT></DOC>